<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-150  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 150.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Jan 1 1990 v12 n1 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Languages, tools came a long way. (programming languages anddevelopment tools for microcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnston, Stuart J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Programming languages and development tools for microcomputersprogressed from assemblers and crude BASIC implementations tointegrated C and Pascal environments during the 1980s, andobservers expect even more dramatic changes in the 1990s.andP;  The'medium-level' C language and the introduction of integratedprogramming and debugging tools were among the most importantdevelopments.andP;  Programmers can now debug in software instead ofusing hardware debuggers.andP;  Borland International Inc's TurboPascal was the first truly structured microcomputer programmingenvironment; Microsoft Corp pioneered source-level debuggers withits CodeView.andP;  The COBOL language gained new life with theannouncement of IBM's Application Development/Cycle strategy.andO;Analysts expect a tremendous increase in the user ofobject-oriented programming in the 1990s; many consider this atruly revolutionary development.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     History of ComputingReview of Past YearFuture of ComputingTrendsProgram Development ToolsProgramming LanguagesObject-Oriented Programming.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>